    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - IC BUS SERVICE MANUAL - BUS BODY CONSTRUCTION - BODY TIE
        DOWN BOLTS
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="describe" graphiccount="3">
        <title>BODY TIE DOWN BOLTS</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Description</title>
            <para>The body tie down bolts are mechanical fasteners that secure the body floor panels to the chassis
                frame rail. This application consists of a combination of body tie down clips and &#189;" - 13 x 11&#189;"
                bolts and nuts equipped with j-bars that fit around the chassis frame rails. A high durometer
                anti-squeak rubber is located between the bus body floor and the chassis frame rail. The anti-squeak
                function is to absorb shock and dampen sound and vibration. Anti-squeak should be in place before the
                tie down bolts are re-torqued.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Maintenance</title>
            <para>The body tie down bolts should be tightened within 30 days or 1,000-2,000 miles and quarterly
                thereafter. The tie down bolts should be torqued 35-40 ft. lbs. The body tie down bolts, front outrigger
                mounting bolts, shear bolts and standard tie downs should be part of a normal preventative maintenance
                check. Refer to
                <hotlnk xrefid="f4700144">Figure 42</hotlnk>, for mounting details.
            </para>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Failure to properly torque tie down bolts can result in body damage.</para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
        </svcsubproc>
